edu.mines.csci598.recycler.backend
Class GameState

java.lang.Object
  edu.mines.csci598.recycler.backend.GameState
All Implemented Interfaces:
InputReceiver
public abstract class GameState
extends java.lang.Object
implements InputReceiver

Encapsulates a "state" of the game. A state defines how status is updated, how graphics are drawn, and how input is handled. A state may have substates, which are (by default) run instead of the upper state when present; these subStates must use the same view matrices as the upper ones. Subclasses do not need to be thread-safe; the game manager will ensure that no more than one thread operates upon the root state at any given time. Note that there is NO thread affinity --- there is no guarantee that any particular set of invocations will occur on any particular threads.

update

public GameState update(float elapsedTime)
Updates this state or its subordinate, given the time elapsed, in seconds. Subclasses will generally want to override updateThis() instead.

Parameters:
elapsedTime - The time that has passed (or that is to be assumed to have passed) since the last call to update(), in seconds
Returns:
The state to continue running, or null to terminate (ie, this to keep running, another state to switch, null to terminate)

updateThis

protected abstract GameState updateThis(float elapsedTime)
Performs updates specific to this state, when it has not subordinate.

Parameters:
elapsedTime - The time elapsed since the last call to update(), in seconds (NOT since the last call to updateThis()!)
Returns:
The state to continue running, or null to terminate.

draw

public void draw(java.awt.Graphics2D g)
Draws this state or its subordinate using the given graphics object. Most subclasses will want to implement drawThis() instead. The method MUST keep matrix pushes/pops balanced; the model matrix can be assumed to be identity; the method MUST NOT leave the view matrix in a modified state upon returning.

receiveInputThis

protected void receiveInputThis(InputEvent e)
Processes an input event which occurred while this state had no subordinate. This is generally preferable to overriding receiveInput() since it does not need to worry about the hierarchy. Default does nothing.
